ko City, Saitama 351-0198, Japan. Electronic address: yyoshiki@riken.jp.\")\n\nAffiliations Expand\n\n### Affiliations\n\n-   1 Structural Glycobiology Team, Systems Glycobiology Research Group, RIKEN-Max Planck Joint Research Center, RIKEN Global Research Cluster, 2-1 Hirosawa, Wako City, Saitama 351-0198, Japan.\n-   2 Research Institute for Microbial Diseases and WPI Immunology Frontier Research Center, Osaka University, Suita, Osaka 565-0871, Japan.\n-   3 Research Institute for Microbial Diseases and WPI Immunology Frontier Research Center, Osaka University, Suita, Osaka 565-0871, Japan; Key Laboratory of Carbohydrate Chemistry and Biotechnology, Ministry of Education, School of Biotechnology, Jiangnan University, Wuxi, Jiangsu 214122, China.\n-   4 Structural Glycobiology Team, Systems Glycobiology Research Group, RIKEN-Max Planck Joint Research Center, RIKEN Global Research Cluster, 2-1 Hirosawa, Wako City, Saitama 351-0198, Japan. Electronic address: yyoshiki@riken.jp.\n\n-   PMID: **27569046**\n-   DOI: [10.1016/j.jmb.2016.08.023](https://doi.org/10.1016/j.jmb.2016.08.023)\n\nItem in Clipboard\n\n# 3D Structure and Interaction of p24β and p24δ Golgi Dynamics Domains: Implication for p24 Complex Formation and Cargo Transport\n\nMasamichi Nagae et al. J Mol Biol. 2016.\n\nShow details\n\nDisplay options\n\nDisplay options\n\nFormat Abstract PubMed PMID\n\nJ Mol Biol\n\nActions\n\n-   [Search in PubMed](/?term=%22J+Mol+Biol%22%5Bjour%5D&sort=date&sort_order=desc)\n-   [Search in NLM Catalog](https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/nlmcatalog?term=%22J+Mol+Biol%22%5BTitle+Abbreviation%5D)\n-   [Add to Search](#)\n\n. 2016 Oct 9;428(20):4087-4099.\n\ndoi: 10.1016/j.jmb.2016.08.023. Epub 2016 Aug 25.\n\n### Authors\n\n[Masamichi Nagae](/?term=Nagae+M&cauthor_id=27569046)  [1](#short-view-affiliation-1 \"Structural Glycobiology Team, Systems Glycobiology Research Group, RIKEN-Max Planck Joint Research Center, RIKEN Global Research Cluster, 2-1 Hirosawa, Wako City, Saitama 351-0198, Japan.\") , [Tetsuya Hirata](/?term=Hirata+T&cauthor_id=27569046)  [2](#short-view-affiliation-2 \"Research Institute for Microbial Diseases and WPI Immunology Frontier Research Center, Osaka University, Suita, Osaka 565-0871, Japan.\") , [Kana Morita-Matsumoto](/?term=Morita-Matsumoto+K&cauthor_id=27569046)  [1](#short-view-affiliation-1 \"Structural Glycobiology Team, Systems Glycobiology Research Group, RIKEN-Max Planck Joint Research Center, RIKEN Global Research Cluster, 2-1 Hirosawa, Wako City, Saitama 351-0198, Japan.\") , [Romina Theiler](/?term=Theiler+R&cauthor_id=27569046)  [2](#short-view-affiliation-2 \"Research Institute for Microbial Diseases and WPI Immunology Frontier Research Center, Osaka University, Suita, Osaka 565-0871, Japan.\") , [Morihisa Fujita](/?term=Fujita+M&cauthor_id=27569046)  [3](#short-view-affiliation-3 \"Research Institute for Microbial Diseases and WPI Immunology Frontier Research Center, Osaka University, Suita, Osaka 565-0871, Japan; Key Laboratory of Carbohydrate Chemistry and Biotechnology, Ministry of Education, School of Biotechnology, Jiangnan University, Wuxi, Jiangsu 214122, China.\") , [Taroh Kinoshita](/?term=Kinoshita+T&cauthor_id=27569046)  [2](#short-view-affiliation-2 \"Research Institute for Microbial Diseases and WPI Immunology Frontier Research Center, Osaka University, Suita, Osaka 565-0871, Japan.\") , [Yoshiki Yamaguchi](/?term=Yamaguchi+Y&cauthor_id=27569046)  [4](#short-view-affiliation-4 \"Structural Glycobiology Team, Systems Glycobiology Research Group, RIKEN-Max Planck Joint Research Center, RIKEN Global Research Cluster, 2-1 Hirosawa, Wako City, Saitama 351-0198, Japan. Electronic address: yyoshiki@riken.jp.\")\n\n### Affiliations\n\n-   1 Structural Glycobiology Team, Systems Glycobiology Research Group, RIKEN-Max Planck Joint Research Center, RIKEN Global Research Cluster, 2-1 Hirosawa, Wako City, Saitama 351-0198, Japan.\n-   2 Research Institute for Microbial Diseases and WPI Immunology Frontier Research Center, Osaka University, Suita, Osaka 565-0871, Japan.\n-   3 Research Institute for Microbial Diseases and WPI Immunology Frontier Research Center, Osaka University, Suita, Osaka 565-0871, Japan; Key Laboratory of Carbohydrate Chemistry and Biotechnology, Ministry of Education, School of Biotechnology, Jiangnan University, Wuxi, Jiangsu 214122, China.\n-   4 Structural Glycobiology Team, Systems Glycobiology Research Group, RIKEN-Max Planck Joint Research Center, RIKEN Global Research Cluster, 2-1 Hirosawa, Wako City, Saitama 351-0198, Japan. Electronic address: yyoshiki@riken.jp.\n\n-   PMID: **27569046**\n-   DOI: [10.1016/j.jmb.2016.08.023](https://doi.org/10.1016/j.jmb.2016.08.023)\n\nItem in Clipboard\n\nFull text links Cite\n\nDisplay options\n\nDisplay options\n\nFormat AbstractPubMedPMID\n\n## Abstract\n\nThe p24 family consists of four subfamilies (p24α, p24β, p24γ, and p24δ), and the proteins are thought to form hetero-oligomeric complexes for efficient transport of cargo proteins from the endoplasmic reticulum to the Golgi apparatus. The proteins possess a conserved luminal Golgi dynamics (GOLD) domain, whose functions are largely unknown. Here, we present structural and biochemical studies of p24β1 and p24δ1 GOLD domains. Use of GOLD domain-deleted mutants revealed that the GOLD domain of p24δ1 is required for proper p24 hetero-oligomeric complex formation and efficient transport of GPI-anchored proteins. The p24β1 and p24δ1 GOLD domains share a common β-sandwich fold with a characteristic intrasheet disulfide bond. The GOLD domain of p24δ1 crystallized as dimers, allowing the analysis of a homophilic interaction site. Surface plasmon resonance and solution NMR analyses revealed that p24β1 and p24δ1 GOLD domains interact weakly (Kd\\= ~10\\-4M). Bi-protein titration provided interaction site maps. We propose that the heterophilic interaction of p24 GOLD domains contributes to the formation of the p24 hetero-oligomeric complex and to efficient cargo transport.\n\n**Keywords:** GOLD domain; GPI-anchored protein; cargo receptor; p24 family; protein transport.\n\nCopyright © 2016 Elsevier Ltd. All rights reserved.\n\n[PubMed Disclaimer](/disclaimer/)\n\n## MeSH terms\n\n-   Cell Line\n    \n    Actions\n    \n    -   [Search in PubMed](/?term=%22Cell+Line%22%5BMeSH%5D&sort=date&sort_order=desc)\n    -   [Search in MeSH](https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/mesh?term=Cell+Line)\n    -   [Add to Search](#)\n    \n-   Crystallography, X-Ray\n    \n    Actions\n    \n    -   [Search in PubMed](/?term=%22Crystallography%2C+X-Ray%22%5BMeSH%5D&sort=date&sort_order=desc)\n    -   [Search in MeSH](https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/mesh?term=Crystallography%2C+X-Ray)\n    -   [Add to Search](#)\n    \n-   Golgi Apparatus / metabolism\\*\n    \n    Actions\n    \n    -   [Search in PubMed](/?term=%22Golgi+Apparatus%2Fmetabolism%22%5BMAJR%5D&sort=date&sort_order=desc)\n    -   [Search in MeSH](https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/mesh?term=Golgi+Apparatus)\n    -   [Add to Search](#)\n    \n-   Humans\n    \n    Actions\n    \n    -   [Search in PubMed](/?term=%22Humans%22%5BMeSH%5D&sort=date&sort_order=desc)\n    -   [Search in MeSH](https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/mesh?term=Humans)\n    -   [Add to Search](#)\n    \n-   Magnetic Resonance Spectroscopy\n    \n    Actions\n    \n    -   [Search in PubMed](/?term=%22Magnetic+Resonance+Spectroscopy%22%5BMeSH%5D&sort=date&sort_order=desc)\n    -   [Search in MeSH](https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/mesh?term=Magnetic+Resonance+Spectroscopy)\n    -   [Add to Search](#)\n    \n-   Membrane Proteins / chemistry\\*\n    \n    Actions\n    \n    -   [Search in PubMed](/?term=%22Membrane+Proteins%2Fchemistry%22%5BMAJR%5D&sort=date&sort_order=desc)\n    -   [Search in MeSH](https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/mesh?term=Membrane+Proteins)\n    -   [Add to Search](#)\n    \n-   Membrane Proteins / metabolism\\*\n    \n    Actions\n    \n    -   [Search in PubMed](/?term=%22Membrane+Proteins%2Fmetabolism%22%5BMAJ