{"type":"tool_use","timestamp":1778987806459,"sessionID":"ses_1cc17a755ffeHlmzTMQRuy0Np3","part":{"type":"tool","tool":"apply_patch","callID":"call_g0KZwvveKEnoAlS3cLdAd7kZ","state":{"status":"completed","input":{"patchText":"*** Begin Patch\n*** Add File: /__w/eval-ont-agent-go/eval-ont-agent-go/DESIGN_PATTERNS.md\n+## Relevant design pattern assessment for issue #31295\n+\n+- Target term type: specific membrane-associated cargo receptor complex in `cellular_component`\n+- Parent precedent: `GO:0062137 cargo receptor complex`\n+- Similar child precedent: `GO:0061852 retrograde cargo receptor complex, Golgi to ER`\n+\n+### Pattern conclusions\n+\n+- There is no dedicated DOSDP needed for this term.\n+- Existing GO precedent for specific cargo receptor complexes favors a simple asserted `is_a` to `cargo receptor complex` plus biologically justified `relationship` tags.\n+- No `intersection_of` axioms should be added here because the requested class is a named biological complex, not a straightforward genus-differentia compositional class with a documented DP.\n+\n+### Modeling choice\n+\n+- Use one asserted parent: `GO:0062137 cargo receptor complex`\n+- Add `relationship: capable_of_part_of GO:0006888 ! endoplasmic reticulum to Golgi vesicle-mediated transport`\n+- Do not add `part_of GO:0070971 ! endoplasmic reticulum exit site`; localization to ER exit sites is important biologically but is context-dependent and weaker than the core identity of the complex.\n*** Add File: /__w/eval-ont-agent-go/eval-ont-agent-go/RESEARCH.md\n+## PMID:19566487 \"The p24 family and selective transport processes at the ER-Golgi interface\"\n+\n+Review of p24 family proteins in the early secretory pathway. Supports modeling p24 proteins as membrane proteins present at the ER-Golgi interface that bind COPI and COPII coats and participate in selective cargo transport.\n+\n+* SUPPORT: PMID:19566487 \"Type-I transmembrane proteins of approximately 24 kDa are abundantly present in the membranes of the early secretory pathway, and bind the COPI and COPII coat complexes that cover vesicles travelling between the membranes.\"\n+    - p24 proteins are membrane-associated early secretory pathway proteins\n+    - they connect to COPI/COPII trafficking machinery\n+\n+* SUPPORT: PMID:19566487 \"These p24 proteins are thought to play an important role in the selective transport processes at the ER-Golgi interface\"\n+    - supports defining the complex around selective cargo transport at the ER-Golgi interface\n+\n+## PMID:32456004 \"Dual Independent Roles of the p24 Complex in Selectivity of Secretory Cargo Export from the Endoplasmic Reticulum\"\n+\n+Primary support for the requested term as a cargo receptor complex involved in ER export. Establishes the p24 complex as a specific cargo receptor complex and supports its role in selective export from the ER.\n+\n+* SUPPORT: PMID:32456004 \"The p24 protein complex acts as a specific cargo receptor for GPI-anchored proteins by facilitating their ER exit through a specialized export pathway in yeast.\"\n+    - supports the parentage under cargo receptor complex\n+    - supports the anterograde ER export role\n+\n+* SUPPORT: PMID:32456004 \"Our results suggest that, in addition to its role as a cargo receptor in the specialized GPI-AP export pathway, the p24 complex also plays an independent role in secretory cargo selectivity during its exit through the general ER export pathway\"\n+    - supports broader cargo selectivity language in the definition\n+\n+## PMID:34647572 \"Differential use of p24 family members as cargo receptors for the transport of glycosylphosphatidylinositol-anchored proteins and Wnt1\"\n+\n+Supports that p24 complexes are bona fide cargo receptor complexes and that a complex generally contains representatives of all four p24 subfamilies.\n+\n+* SUPPORT: PMID:34647572 \"Complexes of p24 proteins act as cargo receptors for the transport of COPII vesicles from the endoplasmic reticulum (ER).\"\n+    - supports cargo receptor complex status in ER-to-Golgi trafficking\n+\n+* SUPPORT: PMID:34647572 \"Each p24 complex is known to contain members from all four p24 subfamilies (p24α, p24β, p24γ and p24δ).\"\n+    - supports describing the complex as conserved and hetero-oligomeric\n+\n+## PMID:27569046 \"3D Structure and Interaction of p24β and p24δ Golgi Dynamics Domains: Implication for p24 Complex Formation and Cargo Transport\"\n+\n+Supports p24 hetero-oligomeric complex formation and cargo transport function.\n+\n+* SUPPORT: PMID:27569046 \"The proteins are thought to form hetero-oligomeric complexes for efficient transport of cargo proteins from the endoplasmic reticulum to the Golgi apparatus.\"\n+    - supports definition wording around hetero-oligomeric complex and ER-to-Golgi cargo transport\n+\n+## PMID:26224213 \"p24 family proteins: key players in the regulation of trafficking along the secretory pathway\"\n+\n+Broad review support that p24 family proteins regulate trafficking in the ER/Golgi secretory pathway and modulate specific cargos.\n+\n+* SUPPORT: PMID:26224213 \"they are emerging as essential regulators of protein trafficking along the secretory pathway, influencing the composition, structure, and function of different organelles in the pathway, especially the ER and the Golgi apparatus.\"\n+    - supports broader secretory-pathway context\n+\n+* SUPPORT: PMID:26224213 \"they appear to modulate the transport of specific cargos, including GPI-anchored proteins\"\n+    - supports specific cargo selection language\n*** End Patch"},"output":"Success. Updated the following files:\nA DESIGN_PATTERNS.md\nA RESEARCH.md","metadata":{"diff":"Index: /__w/eval-ont-agent-go/eval-ont-agent-go/DESIGN_PATTERNS.md\n===================================================================\n--- /__w/eval-ont-agent-go/eval-ont-agent-go/DESIGN_PATTERNS.md\n+++ /__w/eval-ont-agent-go/eval-ont-agent-go/DESIGN_PATTERNS.md\n@@ -0,0 +1,17 @@\n+## Relevant design pattern assessment for issue #31295\n+\n+- Target term type: specific membrane-associated cargo receptor complex in `cellular_component`\n+- Parent precedent: `GO:0062137 cargo receptor complex`\n+- Similar child precedent: `GO:0061852 retrograde cargo receptor complex, Golgi to ER`\n+\n+### Pattern conclusions\n+\n+- There is no dedicated DOSDP needed for this term.\n+- Existing GO precedent for specific cargo receptor complexes favors a simple asserted `is_a` to `cargo receptor complex` plus biologically justified `relationship` tags.\n+- No `intersection_of` axioms should be added here because the requested class is a named biological complex, not a straightforward genus-differentia compositional class with a documented DP.\n+\n+### Modeling choice\n+\n+- Use one asserted parent: `GO:0062137 cargo receptor complex`\n+- Add `relationship: capable_of_part_of GO:0006888 ! endoplasmic reticulum to Golgi vesicle-mediated transport`\n+- Do not add `part_of GO:0070971 ! endoplasmic reticulum exit site`; localization to ER exit sites is important biologically but is context-dependent and weaker than the core identity of the complex.\n\nIndex: /__w/eval-ont-agent-go/eval-ont-agent-go/RESEARCH.md\n===================================================================\n--- /__w/eval-ont-agent-go/eval-ont-agent-go/RESEARCH.md\n+++ /__w/eval-ont-agent-go/eval-ont-agent-go/RESEARCH.md\n@@ -0,0 +1,48 @@\n+## PMID:19566487 \"The p24 family and selective transport processes at the ER-Golgi interface\"\n+\n+Review of p24 family proteins in the early secretory pathway. Supports modeling p24 proteins as membrane proteins present at the ER-Golgi interface that bind COPI and COPII coats and participate in selective cargo transport.\n+\n+* SUPPORT: PMID:19566487 \"Type-I transmembrane proteins of approximately 24 kDa are abundantly present in the membranes of the early secretory pathway, and bind the COPI and COPII coat complexes that cover vesicles travelling between the membranes.\"\n+    - p24 proteins are membrane-associated early secretory pathway proteins\n+    - they connect to COPI/COPII trafficking machinery\n+\n+* SUPPORT: PMID:19566487 \"These p24 proteins are thought to play an important role in the selective transport processes at the ER-Golgi interface\"\n+    - supports defining the complex around selective cargo transport at the ER-Golgi interface\n+\n+## PMID:32456004 \"Dual Independent Roles of the p24 Complex in Selectivity of Secretory Cargo Export from the Endoplasmic Reticulum\"\n+\n+Primary support for the requested term as a cargo receptor complex involved in ER export. Establishes the p24 complex as a specific cargo receptor complex and supports its role in selective export from the ER.\n+\n+* SUPPORT: PMID:32456004 \"The p24 protein complex acts as a specific cargo receptor for GPI-anchored proteins by facilitating their ER exit through a specialized export pathway in yeast.\"\n+    - supports the parentage under cargo receptor complex\n+    - supports the anterograde ER export role\n+\n+* SUPPORT: PMID:32456004 \"Our results suggest that, in addition to its role as a cargo receptor in the specialized GPI-AP export pathway, the p24 complex also plays an independent role in secretory cargo selectivity during its exit through the general ER export pathway\"\n+    - supports broader cargo selectivity language in the definition\n+\n+## PMID:34647572 \"Differential use of p24 family members as cargo receptors for the transport of glycosylphosphatidylinositol-anchored proteins and Wnt1\"\n+\n+Supports that p24 complexes are bona fide cargo receptor complexes and that a complex generally contains representatives of all four p24 subfamilies.\n+\n+* SUPPORT: PMID:34647572 \"Complexes of p24 proteins act as cargo receptors for the transport of COPII vesicles from the endoplasmic reticulum (ER).\"\n+    - supports cargo receptor complex status in ER-to-Golgi trafficking\n+\n+* SUPPORT: PMID:34647572 \"Each p24 complex is known to contain members from all four p24 subfamilies (p24α, p24β, p24γ and p24δ).\"\n+    - supports describing the complex as conserved and hetero-oligomeric\n+\n+## PMID:27569046 \"3D Structure and Interaction of p24β and p24δ Golgi Dynamics Domains: Implication for p24 Complex Formation and Cargo Transport\"\n+\n+Supports p24 hetero-oligomeric complex formation and cargo transport function.\n+\n+* SUPPORT: PMID:27569046 \"The proteins are thought to form hetero-oligomeric complexes for efficient transport of cargo proteins from the endoplasmic reticulum to the Golgi apparatus.\"\n+    - supports definition wording around hetero-oligomeric complex and ER-to-Golgi cargo transport\n+\n+## PMID:26224213 \"p24 family proteins: key players in the regulation of trafficking along the secretory pathway\"\n+\n+Broad review support that p24 family proteins regulate trafficking in the ER/Golgi secretory pathway and modulate specific cargos.\n+\n+* SUPPORT: PMID:26224213 \"they are emerging as essential regulators of protein trafficking along the secretory pathway, influencing the composition, structure, and function of different organelles in the pathway, especially the ER and the Golgi apparatus.\"\n+    - supports broader secretory-pathway context\n+\n+* SUPPORT: PMID:26224213 \"they appear to modulate the transport of specific cargos, including GPI-anchored proteins\"\n+    - supports specific cargo selection language\n\n","files":[{"filePath":"/__w/eval-ont-agent-go/eval-ont-agent-go/DESIGN_PATTERNS.md","relativePath":"DESIGN_PATTERNS.md","type":"add","patch":"Index: /__w/eval-ont-agent-go/eval-ont-agent-go/DESIGN_PATTERNS.md\n===================================================================\n--- /__w/eval-ont-agent-go/eval-ont-agent-go/DESIGN_PATTERNS.md\n+++ /__w/eval-ont-agent-go/eval-ont-agent-go/DESIGN_PATTERNS.md\n@@ -0,0 +1,17 @@\n+## Relevant design pattern assessment for issue #31295\n+\n+- Target term type: specific membrane-associated cargo receptor complex in `cellular_compo